  "response_text": "Vaccines work by stimulating the immune system to recognize and fight off specific pathogens, such as viruses or bacteria, without causing the disease itself. Here\u2019s a step-by-step explanation of how vaccines function:\n\n1. **Introduction of Antigen**: Vaccines contain antigens, which are substances that mimic parts of a virus or bacteria. These antigens are usually weakened, killed versions of the pathogen, or pieces of the pathogen like proteins or sugars. Some vaccines use harmless viruses that have been modified to produce these antigens.\n\n2. **Immune System Recognition**: When you receive a vaccine, your immune system recognizes these antigens as foreign invaders. This triggers an immune response, including the production of antibodies and activation of immune cells like T-cells.\n\n3. **Production of Memory Cells**: In addition to producing antibodies, the immune system also creates memory cells. These are specialized immune cells that \"remember\" the specific antigen. If you are exposed to the actual pathogen in the future",
